x4freetext: 22 ug/cm2 (39 to 13 keV) thick target
(on a 0.2 mm thick Ta backing) enriched to 90% in 13C.
The air-cooled target (40 mm in diameter) was
installed in an electrically insulated pipe of 0.80 m
length, which served as a long Faraday cup.
A 4-pi detector consisting of thermal-
neutron detectors, i.e.,16 3He-filled proportional
counters (sensitive length=45.7 cm, diam.=2.54 cm,
pressure=4 bar), embedded in a polyethylene-cylinder
moderator (length=1.00 m, diam.=35.0 cm) with a centra
bore hole (diam.=7.0 cm) to install the target.
The neutron detection efficiency was calculated by MCNP
and shows good agreement with calibration by 252Cf at
Number of projectiles was determined by
current integrator.
For nonresonant energies, where the yields change
slowly with energy, the observed yields (and thus the
cross sections) are associated with an effective
energy Eeff over the target thickness d(Ea).
For energies with resonance structures, where the
resonance width is comparable to the target thickness,
the deduced value Eeff and associated yield represents
a mean cross section over delta(Ea).
Proofread by Sotirios Harissopulos (2013-03-20)
On. DETECTOR moved from subentry 002.
Sub 002 was corrected.  Error description
and data presentation in sub 002, 003 was changed.
REL-REF and CRITIQUE records were added in sub 004.
Gamma ray detection with a 12*12 inch NaI
crystal in close geometry, placed at another beam line.
The deduced target thickness for the enriched target
was dp=3.25+-0.1 keV, consistent with the value
dp=3.14+-0.1 keV obtained initially.
Enriched C target.
Natural C target (13C=1.1%)

x4freetext: The data from the present experiment at Eeff=1.00 MeV
(157 +/- 7 ub) is in good agreement with the previous
value of 146 +/- 7 ub (C.R.Brune et al., 1993).
Their weighted average (152 +/- 5 ub) was adopted as
the reference value.
W.A.Peters (2017): the reported 13C(a,n)16O cross
sections above 5 MeV may be overcalculated by
nearly 50 %.
With the relative error of 2% and absolute error of 3%,
one arrives at an overall accuracy of 4% for the data
of the present work.
